Orthographical error? In GEN 36:11, the BHS Hebrew is צְפ֥וֹ [tsepho].  Rahlfs Septuaginta more closely aligns to Zepho than Zephi.
Orthographical error? In GEN 36:22, the BHS Hebrew is הֵימָם [hiymam].  Rahlfs Septuaginta more closely aligns to Himam than Homam.
Orthographical error? In GEN 36:23, the BHS Hebrew is עַלְוָ֥ן [alvan].  The Strongs reference for this name points to עַלְוָן [alvan] (with a vav) rather than עַלְיָ֧ן [aliyan] (with a yod).
Orthographical error? In GEN 36:26, the BHS Hebrew is חֶמְדָּ֥ן [chemdan].  The Rahlfs' Septuaginta of 1CH 1:41 more closely aligns to Hamran with Εμερων [Emerōn].
Orthographical error? In GEN 36:27, the BHS Hebrew is עֲקָן [aqan].  The Rahlfs' Septuaginta of 1CH 1:42 more closely aligns to Jaakan with Ιωκαν [Iōkan].
Orthographical error? In GEN 36:39, the BHS Hebrew is הֲדַ֔ר [hadar].  The Rahlfs' Septuaginta of 1CH 1:50 more closely aligns to Hadad with Αδαδ [Adad].
Orthographical error? In GEN 36:40, the BHS Hebrew is עַֽלְוָ֖ה [alvah] although some minority manuscripts contain עַלְיָה [aliyah].

The Hebrew of GEN 38:2 translates as "daughter [bat] of a certain Canaanite whose name was Shua [shua];".  1CH 2:3 treats this as a name Bat-shua rather than a title (daughter of Shua).  The Greek of Rahlfs 1CH 2:3 treats it as "daughter of Shua".
